<div id="review_623967776" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/623967776" />
    <a title="Amber" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5005647-amber"><img alt="Amber" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1349203627p2/5005647.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/623967776?book_show_action=true">May 24, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Amber" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Amber" href="/user/show/5005647-amber">Amber</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5005647-amber?shelf=tech-and-space-and-other-stuff">tech-and-space-and-other-stuff</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer623967776" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10434907220646566833">I won this book in a Goodreads giveaway.<br/><br/>The general storyline is that of one very old man, John Smith, telling the history of the world to a much younger journalist, Susan Krowley. The man had managed to live through what was called the Microsoft Wars that resulted in the destruction of the world as we know it. He reviewed much of known history with more than a bit of speculation and conspiracy theories, especially as it relates to Atlantis and the actions of the Atlantians throughout ancient an</span>
  <span id="freeText10434907220646566833" style="display:none">I won this book in a Goodreads giveaway.<br /><br />The general storyline is that of one very old man, John Smith, telling the history of the world to a much younger journalist, Susan Krowley. The man had managed to live through what was called the Microsoft Wars that resulted in the destruction of the world as we know it. He reviewed much of known history with more than a bit of speculation and conspiracy theories, especially as it relates to Atlantis and the actions of the Atlantians throughout ancient and modern history. With each new era and history that he describes to Ms. Krowley the reader gets to know a little bit more about just how far the world has fallen technologically.<br /><br />The primary reason I had so much trouble reading and making it through this book was because of the format. It is written as an interview in question/answer style. I had hoped for a bit of that maybe at the beginning of chapters or sections with a narrative story otherwise. That is unfair to the author to fault him for my expectations but even once I became accustomed to the style I found it hard to read for more than a few minutes.<br /><br />The second reason I found it hard to read was the strong bias John Smith continued to direct against the various leaders, entrepreneurs and religions he described. On top of that he spoke down at Ms. Krowley, whether intentionally or not I could not determine, in such a way that I had a hard time believing that he truly held the biases he continued to demonstrate. I do not necessarily even disagree with his viewpoints but I was continuously surprised that a reporter did not question further and try to explore the origins of those biases.<br /><br />I did give this book two stars because it was at least an interesting idea. I cannot say whether there were a lot of references to various science fiction stories and television shows as I am a moderate consumer of them. Perhaps others who have explored more of the genre in writing would understand more of the references than I did and appreciate the story put together by Mr. Hughes.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10434907220646566833" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


